1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:05,500
This is quicksort in plain Haskell,
sorting the list [3, 1, 2].

2
00:00:05,500 --> 00:00:10,500
MicroHs (a tiny Haskell compiler) turns it into
combinators: no variables, just tree-rewriting.

3
00:00:10,500 --> 00:00:15,500
Start with the classic core:
the combinators S and K.

4
00:00:15,500 --> 00:00:20,500
K x y = x.
(Keep the first argument, drop the second.)

5
00:00:20,500 --> 00:00:25,500
S x y z = x z (y z).
(Copy z into both branches, then apply.)

6
00:00:25,500 --> 00:00:30,500
S and K alone are Turing-complete:
enough to express any computation.

7
00:00:30,500 --> 00:00:35,500
MicroHs compiles to a richer set: supercombinators.

8
00:00:35,500 --> 00:00:40,500
The rules firing up top, like P, O, J and Y,
are those supercombinators.

9
00:00:40,500 --> 00:00:45,500
Each one still reduces to S and K underneath.

10
00:00:45,500 --> 00:00:50,500
There is an even smaller basis:
a single combinator, ι (iota).

11
00:00:50,500 --> 00:00:55,500
ι = λx. x S K.
Applied to itself, ι ι = I, the identity.

12
00:00:55,500 --> 00:01:00,500
K = ι(ι(ιι)),    S = ι(ι(ι(ιι))).

13
00:01:00,500 --> 00:01:05,500
So S, K, and every supercombinator collapse to ι.

14
00:01:05,500 --> 00:01:10,500
Each step rewrites a combinator,
but every frame is drawn as pure ι.

15
00:01:10,500 --> 00:01:15,500
In the picture, each dot is one ι,
and each branch is an application.

16
00:01:15,500 --> 00:01:20,500
A term is one bit-code:  iota = 0 | 1 iota iota
(0 is ι; 1 applies the next two).

17
00:01:20,500 --> 00:01:25,500
This whole turning mandala is one closed ι-term.

18
00:01:25,500 --> 00:01:30,500
Data is compiled too: each constructor
becomes a function that picks a branch.

19
00:01:30,500 --> 00:01:35,500
Numbers are Peano: a zero,
and the successor (Succ) of a smaller number.

20
00:01:35,500 --> 00:01:40,500
Zero picks the zero branch;
Succ n picks the other, carrying n.

21
00:01:40,500 --> 00:01:45,500
Lists and booleans work the same way,
each compiling to its own combinator.

22
00:01:45,500 --> 00:01:50,500
So this tree is quicksort [3, 1, 2]:
data and code, all of it in ι.

23
00:01:50,500 --> 00:01:55,500
Listen: each combinator family has its own note,
and recursion drops to a low bass.

24
00:01:55,500 --> 00:02:00,500
The algorithm: pick a pivot, split the rest
into ≤ and >, sort each side, join.

25
00:02:00,500 --> 00:02:05,500
That ≤ comparison is the phrase you keep hearing.

26
00:02:05,500 --> 00:02:10,500
The recursion is the Y combinator (Y f → f (Y f)):
each call copies the sorter and expands the tree.

27
00:02:10,700 --> 00:02:13,300
Comparison by comparison,
it reaches the sorted answer: [1, 2, 3].

28
00:02:13,400 --> 00:02:15,600
And to read a list back, we un-cons it:
peel off the head, then the rest.

29
00:02:15,700 --> 00:02:20,500
1, 2, 3.  Sorted, in pure ι.
